# Thrust-to-Weight Ratio

## What is Thrust-to-Weight Ratio?

The thrust-to-weight ratio compares the total thrust produced by the motors to the weight of the aircraft.

It is an important measure because it determines whether the aircraft can take off, hover, climb, and manoeuvre effectively.

---

## Thrust-to-Weight Ratio Formula

Thrust-to-Weight Ratio = Total Thrust / Aircraft Weight

A thrust-to-weight ratio greater than 1 means the aircraft can climb vertically.

---

## Design Values

- Estimated aircraft mass: 3.3 kg
- Aircraft weight:

  Weight = mg

  Weight = 3.3 × 9.81

  Weight = 32.37 N

---

## VTOL Requirement

During vertical take-off, the combined thrust of the four lift motors must exceed the aircraft's weight.

During hover, the combined thrust of the four lift motors must equal the aircraft's weight.

The aircraft should produce significantly more thrust than its weight, in order to keep an adequate saftery margin and improve control.

---

## Application

The four SunnySky X2814 900KV motors were chosen to provide sufficient thrust for vertical take-off and hover.

The forward propulsion motor is used only during forward flight and isn't included in the hover thrust calculation.

The thrust-to-weight ratio will be calculated using manufacturer data and verified through thrust testing after assembly.
